{"title_page": "Marius Fransman", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name            = Marius Fransman\n| image           = File:Visita del Vicecanciller de Sud\u00e1frica (9682283362).jpg\n| caption         = \n| office          = [[Western Cape Provincial Parliament|Leader of the Opposition in the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]\n| term_start      = 21 May 2014\n| term_end        = 16 February 2016\n| predecessor     = [[Lynne Brown]]\n| successor       = Khaya Magaxa \n| office1         = Provincial Chairperson of the [[African National Congress|Western Cape African National Congress]]\n| term_start1     = 12 February 2011\n| term_end1       = February 2016\n| predecessor1    = [[Mcebisi Skwatsha]]\n| successor1      = Khaya Magaxa\n| office2         = [[Department of International Relations and Cooperation|Deputy Minister of International Relations and Cooperation]]\n| term_start2     = 2 November 2010\n| term_end2       = 25 May 2014\n| predecessor2    = Sue van der Merwe\n| successor2      = [[Luwellyn Landers]]\n| office3         = [[National Assembly of South Africa|Member of the National Assembly]]\n| term_start3     = 6 May 2009 \n| term_end3       = 6 May 2014\n| constituency3   = [[Western Cape]]\n{{collapsed infobox section begin|[[Western Cape government]] positions|titlestyle=background-color:#eee}}\n | office4         = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Health]]\n | term_start4     = 1 August 2008\n | term_end4       = 6 May 2009\n | predecessor4    = [[Pierre Uys]]\n | successor4      = [[Theuns Botha]]\n | office5         = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Transport and Public Works]]\n | term_start5     = 26 July 2005\n | term_end5       = 1 August 2008\n | predecessor5    = [[Mcebisi Skwatsha]]\n | successor5      = [[Kholeka Mqulwana]]\n | office6         = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Local Government and Housing]]\n | term_start6     = 30 April 2004\n | term_end6       = 26 July 2005\n | predecessor6    = ''Unknown''\n | successor6      = [[Richard Dyantyi]]\n | office7         = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Social Services and Poverty Alleviation]]\n | term_start7     = 5 December 2001\n | term_end7       = 30 April 2004\n | predecessor7    = [[Peter Marais]]\n | successor7      = [[Kholeka Mqulwana]]\n{{collapsed infobox section end}}\n| office8         = [[Western Cape Provincial Parliament|Member of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]\n| term_start8     = 21 May 2014 \n| term_end8       = 16 September 2016\n| constituency8   = [[City of Cape Town]]\n| term_start9     = 15 June 1999 \n| term_end9       = 6 May 2009\n| constituency9   = [[City of Cape Town]]\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1969|08|15|df=y}}\n| birth_place     = Blackheath, [[Cape Flats]], [[Cape Town]], [[South Africa]]\n| party           = [[African National Congress]] (until 2016)\n| spouse          = Philida Fransman\n| children        = 2\n| alma_mater      = [[University of the Western Cape]]\n| profession      = [[Teacher]]<br />[[Politician]]\n}}\n'''Marius Llewellyn Fransman''' is a retired South African teacher and politician. He previously served as [[Western Cape Provincial Parliament|Leader of the Opposition in the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]] from 2014 to 2016, and [[African National Congress|Chairperson of the Western Cape African National Congress]] from 2011 to 2016. He served as [[Department of International Relations and Cooperation|Deputy Minister of International Relations and Cooperation]] in the cabinet of Jacob Zuma. From 2009 to 2014, he was a [[National Assembly of South Africa|Member of the National Assembly]]. Fransman served as a [[Member of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]] from 1999 to 2009, and again from 2014 to 2016.\n\n==Early life and career==\nFransman was born on 15 August 1969 in Blackheath on the [[Cape Flats]]. He served as head boy of Bishop Lavis Secondary School and matriculated in 1987. He played a crucial role in creating awareness while he served as the chairperson of the school's student representative council (SRC). He obtained a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree from the [[University of Western Cape]]. Later on, he achieved a Higher Diploma in Education from the same university.<ref name=\"News24\">{{cite news |title=From headboy to provincial ANC head honcho: Who is Marius Fransman? |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/from-headboy-to-provincial-anc-head-honcho-who-is-marius-fransman-20160108 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |newspaper=News24 |date=8 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter completing his studies at university, he worked as a teacher in the town of [[Vredendal]]. In that same period, he joined the African National Congress.<ref name=\"News24\" />\n\n==Political career==\n[[File:Marius Fransman.jpg|150px|thumb|left|Fransman campaigning for a by-election candidate in 2007]]\nHe worked as a regional recruiter for the ANC and later took up the position of Farm Dweller Project Manager at Surplus People's Project. He served as Provincial Deputy Secretary of the Western Cape African National Congress branch from 1997 until 2004, while he concurrently worked as head of the fishing desk. He was the party's rural elections co-ordinator from 1995 until he became the party's provincial elections coordinator in 1999.<ref name=\"News24\" />\n\nDespite holding many internal party positions, he served as Deputy Mayor and Mayor of the Vredendal Municipality. He was elected to the Western Cape Provincial Parliament in 1999 and held many positions in the Western Cape provincial government. He was named Provincial Minister of Social Services and Poverty Alleviation in 2001 but was then deployed to the position of Provincial Minister of Local Government and Housing in 2004.<ref>{{cite news |title=New-look cabinet for WCape |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/New-look-cabinet-for-WCape-20011205 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |newspaper=News24 Archives |date=5 December 2001}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Rasool names Western Cape cabinet |url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/rasool-names-western-cape-cabinet-211796 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |newspaper=IOL |date=30 April 2004}}</ref> In 2005, Rasool reshuffled his executive and designated Fransman as Provincial Minister of Transport and Public Works.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rasool names new MECs |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Rasool-names-new-MECs-20050726 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |newspaper=News24 Archives |date=26 July 2005 |location=Cape Town}}</ref> He served until 2008 when Premier [[Lynne Brown]] announced that Fransman would become Provincial Minister of Health.<ref>{{cite news |title=Brown unveils new Cabinet |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Brown-unveils-new-Cabinet-20080801 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |newspaper=News24 |date=1 August 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2009, he was elected to the National Assembly and served as Parliamentary Chairperson of the Higher Education and Training Committee. President [[Jacob Zuma]] reconfigured the national cabinet in October 2010 and named Fransman as Deputy Minister of International Relations and Cooperation, succeeding Sue van der Merwe.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Webb |first1=Boyd |title=Zuma replaces seven ministers in reshuffle |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2010-10-31-zuma-replaces-seven-ministers-in-cabinet-reshuffle/ |accessdate=1 April 2020 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=31 October 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Zuma |first1=Jacob |title=Zuma's cabinet reshuffle |url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/documents/zumas-cabinet-reshuffle |accessdate=1 April 2020 |newspaper=Politicsweb |date=31 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Chairperson of the Western Cape African National Congress==\nFransman was a candidate for the post of Chairperson of the Western Cape African National Congress. The incumbent, [[Mcebisi Skwatsha]], decided to stand down. Fransman was unanimously elected chairperson on 12 February 2011 at the party's conference in [[Cape Town]].<ref>[https://mg.co.za/article/2011-02-12-marius-fransman-crowned-cape-anc-chairperson Marius Fransman crowned Cape ANC Chairperson]</ref>\n\nAs Chairperson of the African National Congress in the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]]-led Western Cape, Fransman came under fire on several occasions before the [[2014 South African general election|2014 general election]] for his controversial [[canvassing]] methods.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mg.co.za/article/2014-04-30-western-cape-food-for-votes-case-in-court |title=Western Cape food for votes case in court |date=30 April 2014 |website= |publisher=Mail & Guardian |accessdate=1 February 2015}}</ref> The methods included distributing food parcels to potential voters and promising large sums of cash to [[Coloured]] voters before the election.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2015/02/01/anc-leader-in-votes-for-cash-scandal1 |title=ANC leader in 'votes for cash' scandal |date=1 February 2015 |website= |publisher=Times Live |accessdate=1 February 2015}}</ref> Fransman was the party's premier candidate. The party retained all its seats in the Western Cape Provincial Parliament and he returned to the Western Cape Provincial Parliament as Leader of the Opposition, succeeding [[Lynne Brown]]. He challenged incumbent [[Helen Zille]] of the Democratic Alliance for the position of Premier at the first sitting of the Fifth Provincial Parliament. He subsequently lost to Zille as the Democratic Alliance held a majority in the Provincial Parliament. Fransman received 14 votes compared Zille's 27 votes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.news24.com/Elections/News/Zille-re-elected-Western-Cape-premier-20140521 |title=Zille re-elected Western Cape premier |access-date=2018-12-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181205124510/https://www.news24.com/Elections/News/Zille-re-elected-Western-Cape-premier-20140521 |archive-date=2018-12-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nFransman had also challenged and criticised the Western Cape Government and the Democratic Alliance on its policy positions. Fransman won re-election unopposed to a second term at the party's conference in 2015.<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/Fransman-re-elected-as-WCape-ANC-chair-20150628 Fransman re-elected as Western Cape ANC Chair]</ref>\n\n===Sexual harassment allegations===\nFransman was accused of [[sexual assault]] by his assistant, Louisa Wynand. Fransman was alleged to have sexually assaulted Wynand while ''en route'' to the African National Congress's 104th birthday celebrations in [[Rustenburg]] in January 2016.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Thamm |first1=Marianne |title=Marius Fransman\u2019s sexual assault charge & ANC Western Cape\u2019s tipping point |url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2016-01-12-marius-fransmans-sexual-assault-charge-anc-western-capes-tipping-point/ |accessdate=1 April 2020 |newspaper=The Daily Maverick |date=12 January 2016}}</ref> Fransman strongly denied these claims.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gqirana |first1=Thulani |title=ANC Western Cape leader Marius Fransman says sexual harassment allegations just 'nonsense' |url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2016-01-16-anc-western-cape-leader-marius-fransman-says-sexual-harassment-allegations-just-nonsense/ |accessdate=1 April 2020 |newspaper=TimesLIVE |date=16 January 2016}}</ref> The Democratic Alliance, as well as party officials from the African National Congress, called for him to step down.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bernardo |first1=Carla |title=DA protesters call for Fransman to resign |url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/da-protesters-call-for-fransman-to-resign-1971723 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |newspaper=IOL |date=15 January 2016 |location=Cape Town}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Quintal |first1=Genevieve |title=Fransman has no choice but to step down - Mantashe |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/fransman-has-no-choice-but-to-step-down-mantashe-20160128 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |newspaper=News24 |date=28 January 2016 |location=Johannesburg}}</ref> The party quickly suspended Fransman as chairperson pending an investigation into the alleged assault claims. Deputy Chairperson, Khaya Magaxa, was designated as Fransman's acting successor. On 16 February 2016, it was announced that Magaxa would succeed Fransman as Leader of the Opposition in the Western Cape Provincial Parliament. The ANC said that Magaxa would replace Fransman until all the internal processes had been completed.<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/khaya-magaxa-replaces-fransman-in-western-cape-legislature-20160216 Khaya Magaxa replaces Fransman in the Western Cape legislature]</ref>\n\nFransman had received quite a lot of support during this period. In February 2016, a Facebook page was created with the name, ''Friends of Marius Fransman''. On the page, a prayer service was organised for the Fransman family. The service was later held in Vredendal. In April 2016, the secretary of the provincial ANC Youth League called for the reinstatement of Fransman.<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/western-cape-ancyl-distances-itself-from-calls-for-fransmans-return-20160415 Western Cape ANCYL distances itself from calls for Fransman's return]</ref><ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/thousands-join-friends-of-fransman-facebook-page-20160206 Thousands join 'Friends of Fransman' Facebook page]</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, the National Prosecuting Authority announced that the charges against Fransman had been dropped due to a lack of evidence. The African National Congress continued with its own party investigation.<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/sexual-harrassment-charges-dropped-against-fransman-npa-20160523 Sexual harassment charges dropped against Fransman - NPA]</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, the African National Congress Women's League stated that the organisation would not support Fransman, as well as his accuser.<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/ancwl-wont-support-comrade-fransman-20160623 ANCWL won't support 'comrade' Fransman]</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, an ANC official claimed that Fransman had returned to his position. ANC Secretary-General, [[Gwede Mantashe]], criticised the party official who made the false announcement. Fransman brought forward a court application to get reinstated as chairperson.<ref>[https://www.news24.com/Elections/News/mantashe-hits-out-at-zuma-mokonyane-for-endorsing-fransman-20160725 Fransman is not back - Mantashe]</ref>\n\nIn August 2016, the African National Congress's support in the Western Cape significantly decreased. The party lost many wards and municipalities to the Democratic Alliance.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Magubane |first1=Khulekani |title=Baleka Mbete blames leaders for ANC decline in Western Cape |url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/national/2016-08-29-baleka-mbete-blames-leaders-for-anc-decline-in-western-cape/ |accessdate=1 April 2020 |agency=BusinessLIVE |date=29 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Resignation and suspension===\nIn September 2016, Fransman resigned as a Member of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament, yet he did not step down from the position of provincial chairperson.<ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/fransman-quits-western-cape-legislature-2069302 Fransman quits Western Cape leader]</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, the National Disciplinary Committee of the African National Congress found Fransman guilty on two counts of misconduct and suspended his party membership for five years, consequently removing him as chairperson of the provincial branch.<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/anc-suspends-marius-fransman-for-5-years-20161110 ANC suspends Marius Fransman for five years]</ref>\n\n==Post-political career==\nIn March 2017, Fransman threw his support behind chairperson of Nelson Mandela Bay African National Congress branch, Andile Lunigsa, as senior ANC party officials called for Lungisa's resignation.<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/marius-fransmans-ode-to-andile-lungisa-20170323 Marius Fransman's ode to Andile Lungisa]</ref>\n\nFransman, who is an avid supporter of Jacob Zuma, also announced in March 2017, that he is elated that Zuma reshuffled his cabinet and praised the appointments of the new ministers. He challenged the disgruntled ministers and MPs to resign their respective posts.<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/fransman-dares-unhappy-cabinet-ministers-to-resign-20170331 Fransman dares unhappy Cabinet ministers to resign]</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, the South African Jewish Board of Deputies made public statements, in which they stated that Fransman had not yet apologised for the defamatory comments he made in 2013.<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/marius-fransman-has-not-yet-apologised-for-2013-remarks-sa-jewish-board-20180928 Marius Fransman has not yet apologised for 2013 remarks - SA Jewish Board]</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, the National Prosecuting Authority announced that sexual assault claims made by Fransman's accuser, Louisa Wynand, would be investigated.<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/npa-to-prosecute-marius-fransman-20181208 NPA to prosecute Marius Fransman]</ref>\n\nThe sexual assault charges against Fransman were officially dropped in September 2019, after the two parties came to an agreement to settle out of court.<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/npa-withdraws-sexual-assault-charges-against-marius-fransman-20190918 NPA withdraws sexual assault charges against Marius Fransman]. Retrieved on 19 September 2019.</ref> The ANC responded with the lifting of Fransman's suspension as a party member. Interim ANC Western Cape Chair, Lerumo Kalako, has said that Fransman is welcome to become a member of the party again.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2019/09/19/anc-says-fransman-can-return-to-party-after-sex-harassment-charges-withdrawn ANC says Fransman can return to party after sex harassment charges withdrawn]. Retrieved on 19 September 2019.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFransman is married to Philida Fransman. They have two children together. Fransman is a Christian and regularly attends church. He is a fluent speaker of Afrikaans and English.\n\nOn 31 March 2020, Fransman announced that he had tested positive for [[COVID-19]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Clothia |first1=Andrea |title=COVID-19: Former ANC chairperson Marius Fransman tests positive |url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/covid-19-marius-fransman-tests-positive-for-coronavirus/ |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Pijoos |first1=Iavan |title=Former ANC Western Cape chair Marius Fransman tests positive for Covid-19 |url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2020-04-01-former-anc-western-cape-chair-marius-fransman-tests-positive-for-covid-19/ |accessdate=1 April 2020 |newspaper=TimesLIVE |date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==External links==\n*[http://www.dirco.gov.za/department/profile_fransman.html Profile: Mr Marius Llewellyn Fransman \u2013 DIRCO]\n*[https://www.pa.org.za/person/marius-llewellyn-fransman/ Mr Marius Llewellyn Fransman \u2013 People's Assembly]\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box\n | title = [[Western Cape Provincial Parliament|Leader of the Opposition in the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]\n | years = 2014\u20132016\n | before = [[Lynne Brown]]\n | after = Khaya Magaxa\n}}\n{{succession box\n | title = [[Department of International Relations and Cooperation|Deputy Minister of International Relations and Cooperation]]\n | years = 2010\u20132014\n | before = Sue van der Merwe\n | after = [[Luwellyn Landers]]\n}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fransman, Marius}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]\n[[Category:Cape Coloureds]]\n[[Category:African National Congress politicians]]\n[[Category:University of the Western Cape alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:People from Cape Town]]\n[[Category:Members of the National Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:People from the West Coast District Municipality]]\n[[Category:20th-century South African politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century South African politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name            = Marius Fransman\n| image           = File:Visita del Vicecanciller de Sud\u00e1frica (9682283362).jpg\n| caption         = \n| office          = [[Western Cape Provincial Parliament|Leader of the Opposition in the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]\n| term_start      = 21 May 2014\n| term_end        = 16 February 2016\n| predecessor     = [[Lynne Brown]]\n| successor       = Khaya Magaxa \n| office1         = Provincial Chairperson of the [[African National Congress|Western Cape African National Congress]]\n| term_start1     = 12 February 2011\n| term_end1       = February 2016\n| predecessor1    = [[Mcebisi Skwatsha]]\n| successor1      = Khaya Magaxa\n| office2         = [[Department of International Relations and Cooperation|Deputy Minister of International Relations and Cooperation]]\n| term_start2     = 2 November 2010\n| term_end2       = 25 May 2014\n| predecessor2    = Sue van der Merwe\n| successor2      = [[Luwellyn Landers]]\n| office3         = [[National Assembly of South Africa|Member of the National Assembly]]\n| term_start3     = 6 May 2009 \n| term_end3       = 6 May 2014\n| constituency3   = [[Western Cape]]\n | office4         = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Health]]\n | term_start4     = 1 August 2008\n | term_end4       = 6 May 2009\n | predecessor4    = [[Pierre Uys]]\n | successor4      = [[Theuns Botha]]\n | office5         = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Transport and Public Works]]\n | term_start5     = 26 July 2005\n | term_end5       = 1 August 2008\n | predecessor5    = [[Mcebisi Skwatsha]]\n | successor5      = [[Kholeka Mqulwana]]\n | office6         = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Local Government and Housing]]\n | term_start6     = 30 April 2004\n | term_end6       = 26 July 2005\n | predecessor6    = ''Unknown''\n | successor6      = [[Richard Dyantyi]]\n | office7         = [[Government of the Western Cape|Western Cape Provincial Minister of Social Services and Poverty Alleviation]]\n | term_start7     = 5 December 2001\n | term_end7       = 30 April 2004\n | predecessor7    = [[Peter Marais]]\n | successor7      = [[Kholeka Mqulwana]]\n| office8         = [[Western Cape Provincial Parliament|Member of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]\n| term_start8     = 21 May 2014 \n| term_end8       = 16 September 2016\n| constituency8   = [[City of Cape Town]]\n| term_start9     = 15 June 1999 \n| term_end9       = 6 May 2009\n| constituency9   = [[City of Cape Town]]\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1969|08|15|df=y}}\n| birth_place     = Blackheath, [[Cape Flats]], [[Cape Town]], [[South Africa]]\n| party           = [[African National Congress]] (until 2016)\n| spouse          = Philida Fransman\n| children        = 2\n| alma_mater      = [[University of the Western Cape]]\n| profession      = [[Teacher]]<br />[[Politician]]\n}}\n'''Marius Llewellyn Fransman''' is a retired South African teacher and politician. He previously served as [[Western Cape Provincial Parliament|Leader of the Opposition in the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]] from 2014 to 2016, and [[African National Congress|Chairperson of the Western Cape African National Congress]] from 2011 to 2016. He served as [[Department of International Relations and Cooperation|Deputy Minister of International Relations and Cooperation]] in the cabinet of Jacob Zuma. From 2009 to 2014, he was a [[National Assembly of South Africa|Member of the National Assembly]]. Fransman served as a [[Member of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]] from 1999 to 2009, and again from 2014 to 2016.\n\n==Early life and career==\nFransman was born on 15 August 1969 in Blackheath on the [[Cape Flats]]. He served as head boy of Bishop Lavis Secondary School and matriculated in 1987. He played a crucial role in creating awareness while he served as the chairperson of the school's student representative council (SRC). He obtained a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree from the [[University of Western Cape]]. Later on, he achieved a Higher Diploma in Education from the same university.<ref name=\"News24\">{{cite news |title=From headboy to provincial ANC head honcho: Who is Marius Fransman? |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/from-headboy-to-provincial-anc-head-honcho-who-is-marius-fransman-20160108 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |newspaper=News24 |date=8 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter completing his studies at university, he worked as a teacher in the town of [[Vredendal]]. In that same period, he joined the African National Congress.<ref name=\"News24\" />\n\n==Political career==\n[[File:Marius Fransman.jpg|150px|thumb|left|Fransman campaigning for a by-election candidate in 2007]]\nHe worked as a regional recruiter for the ANC and later took up the position of Farm Dweller Project Manager at Surplus People's Project. He served as Provincial Deputy Secretary of the Western Cape African National Congress branch from 1997 until 2004, while he concurrently worked as head of the fishing desk. He was the party's rural elections co-ordinator from 1995 until he became the party's provincial elections coordinator in 1999.<ref name=\"News24\" />\n\nDespite holding many internal party positions, he served as Deputy Mayor and Mayor of the Vredendal Municipality. He was elected to the Western Cape Provincial Parliament in 1999 and held many positions in the Western Cape provincial government. He was named Provincial Minister of Social Services and Poverty Alleviation in 2001 but was then deployed to the position of Provincial Minister of Local Government and Housing in 2004.<ref>{{cite news |title=New-look cabinet for WCape |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/New-look-cabinet-for-WCape-20011205 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |newspaper=News24 Archives |date=5 December 2001}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Rasool names Western Cape cabinet |url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/rasool-names-western-cape-cabinet-211796 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |newspaper=IOL |date=30 April 2004}}</ref> In 2005, Rasool reshuffled his executive and designated Fransman as Provincial Minister of Transport and Public Works.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rasool names new MECs |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Rasool-names-new-MECs-20050726 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |newspaper=News24 Archives |date=26 July 2005 |location=Cape Town}}</ref> He served until 2008 when Premier [[Lynne Brown]] announced that Fransman would become Provincial Minister of Health.<ref>{{cite news |title=Brown unveils new Cabinet |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/Politics/Brown-unveils-new-Cabinet-20080801 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |newspaper=News24 |date=1 August 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2009, he was elected to the National Assembly and served as Parliamentary Chairperson of the Higher Education and Training Committee. President [[Jacob Zuma]] reconfigured the national cabinet in October 2010 and named Fransman as Deputy Minister of International Relations and Cooperation, succeeding Sue van der Merwe.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Webb |first1=Boyd |title=Zuma replaces seven ministers in reshuffle |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2010-10-31-zuma-replaces-seven-ministers-in-cabinet-reshuffle/ |accessdate=1 April 2020 |newspaper=Mail & Guardian |date=31 October 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Zuma |first1=Jacob |title=Zuma's cabinet reshuffle |url=https://www.politicsweb.co.za/documents/zumas-cabinet-reshuffle |accessdate=1 April 2020 |newspaper=Politicsweb |date=31 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Chairperson of the Western Cape African National Congress==\nFransman was a candidate for the post of Chairperson of the Western Cape African National Congress. The incumbent, [[Mcebisi Skwatsha]], decided to stand down. Fransman was unanimously elected chairperson on 12 February 2011 at the party's conference in [[Cape Town]].<ref>[https://mg.co.za/article/2011-02-12-marius-fransman-crowned-cape-anc-chairperson Marius Fransman crowned Cape ANC Chairperson]</ref>\n\nAs Chairperson of the African National Congress in the [[Democratic Alliance (South Africa)|Democratic Alliance]]-led Western Cape, Fransman came under fire on several occasions before the [[2014 South African general election|2014 general election]] for his controversial [[canvassing]] methods.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mg.co.za/article/2014-04-30-western-cape-food-for-votes-case-in-court |title=Western Cape food for votes case in court |date=30 April 2014 |website= |publisher=Mail & Guardian |accessdate=1 February 2015}}</ref> The methods included distributing food parcels to potential voters and promising large sums of cash to [[Coloured]] voters before the election.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2015/02/01/anc-leader-in-votes-for-cash-scandal1 |title=ANC leader in 'votes for cash' scandal |date=1 February 2015 |website= |publisher=Times Live |accessdate=1 February 2015}}</ref> Fransman was the party's premier candidate. The party retained all its seats in the Western Cape Provincial Parliament and he returned to the Western Cape Provincial Parliament as Leader of the Opposition, succeeding [[Lynne Brown]]. He challenged incumbent [[Helen Zille]] of the Democratic Alliance for the position of Premier at the first sitting of the Fifth Provincial Parliament. He subsequently lost to Zille as the Democratic Alliance held a majority in the Provincial Parliament. Fransman received 14 votes compared Zille's 27 votes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.news24.com/Elections/News/Zille-re-elected-Western-Cape-premier-20140521 |title=Zille re-elected Western Cape premier |access-date=2018-12-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181205124510/https://www.news24.com/Elections/News/Zille-re-elected-Western-Cape-premier-20140521 |archive-date=2018-12-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nFransman had also challenged and criticised the Western Cape Government and the Democratic Alliance on its policy positions. Fransman won re-election unopposed to a second term at the party's conference in 2015.<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/Fransman-re-elected-as-WCape-ANC-chair-20150628 Fransman re-elected as Western Cape ANC Chair]</ref>\n\n===Sexual harassment allegations===\nFransman was accused of [[sexual assault]] by his assistant, Louisa Wynand. Fransman was alleged to have sexually assaulted Wynand while ''en route'' to the African National Congress's 104th birthday celebrations in [[Rustenburg]] in January 2016.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Thamm |first1=Marianne |title=Marius Fransman\u2019s sexual assault charge & ANC Western Cape\u2019s tipping point |url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2016-01-12-marius-fransmans-sexual-assault-charge-anc-western-capes-tipping-point/ |accessdate=1 April 2020 |newspaper=The Daily Maverick |date=12 January 2016}}</ref> Fransman strongly denied these claims.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gqirana |first1=Thulani |title=ANC Western Cape leader Marius Fransman says sexual harassment allegations just 'nonsense' |url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/politics/2016-01-16-anc-western-cape-leader-marius-fransman-says-sexual-harassment-allegations-just-nonsense/ |accessdate=1 April 2020 |newspaper=TimesLIVE |date=16 January 2016}}</ref> The Democratic Alliance, as well as party officials from the African National Congress, called for him to step down.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bernardo |first1=Carla |title=DA protesters call for Fransman to resign |url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/da-protesters-call-for-fransman-to-resign-1971723 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |newspaper=IOL |date=15 January 2016 |location=Cape Town}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Quintal |first1=Genevieve |title=Fransman has no choice but to step down - Mantashe |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/fransman-has-no-choice-but-to-step-down-mantashe-20160128 |accessdate=1 April 2020 |newspaper=News24 |date=28 January 2016 |location=Johannesburg}}</ref> The party quickly suspended Fransman as chairperson pending an investigation into the alleged assault claims. Deputy Chairperson, Khaya Magaxa, was designated as Fransman's acting successor. On 16 February 2016, it was announced that Magaxa would succeed Fransman as Leader of the Opposition in the Western Cape Provincial Parliament. The ANC said that Magaxa would replace Fransman until all the internal processes had been completed.<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/khaya-magaxa-replaces-fransman-in-western-cape-legislature-20160216 Khaya Magaxa replaces Fransman in the Western Cape legislature]</ref>\n\nFransman had received quite a lot of support during this period. In February 2016, a Facebook page was created with the name, ''Friends of Marius Fransman''. On the page, a prayer service was organised for the Fransman family. The service was later held in Vredendal. In April 2016, the secretary of the provincial ANC Youth League called for the reinstatement of Fransman.<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/western-cape-ancyl-distances-itself-from-calls-for-fransmans-return-20160415 Western Cape ANCYL distances itself from calls for Fransman's return]</ref><ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/thousands-join-friends-of-fransman-facebook-page-20160206 Thousands join 'Friends of Fransman' Facebook page]</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, the National Prosecuting Authority announced that the charges against Fransman had been dropped due to a lack of evidence. The African National Congress continued with its own party investigation.<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/sexual-harrassment-charges-dropped-against-fransman-npa-20160523 Sexual harassment charges dropped against Fransman - NPA]</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, the African National Congress Women's League stated that the organisation would not support Fransman, as well as his accuser.<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/ancwl-wont-support-comrade-fransman-20160623 ANCWL won't support 'comrade' Fransman]</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, an ANC official claimed that Fransman had returned to his position. ANC Secretary-General, [[Gwede Mantashe]], criticised the party official who made the false announcement. Fransman brought forward a court application to get reinstated as chairperson.<ref>[https://www.news24.com/Elections/News/mantashe-hits-out-at-zuma-mokonyane-for-endorsing-fransman-20160725 Fransman is not back - Mantashe]</ref>\n\nIn August 2016, the African National Congress's support in the Western Cape significantly decreased. The party lost many wards and municipalities to the Democratic Alliance.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Magubane |first1=Khulekani |title=Baleka Mbete blames leaders for ANC decline in Western Cape |url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/national/2016-08-29-baleka-mbete-blames-leaders-for-anc-decline-in-western-cape/ |accessdate=1 April 2020 |agency=BusinessLIVE |date=29 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Resignation and suspension===\nIn September 2016, Fransman resigned as a Member of the Western Cape Provincial Parliament, yet he did not step down from the position of provincial chairperson.<ref>[https://www.iol.co.za/news/politics/fransman-quits-western-cape-legislature-2069302 Fransman quits Western Cape leader]</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, the National Disciplinary Committee of the African National Congress found Fransman guilty on two counts of misconduct and suspended his party membership for five years, consequently removing him as chairperson of the provincial branch.<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/anc-suspends-marius-fransman-for-5-years-20161110 ANC suspends Marius Fransman for five years]</ref>\n\n==Post-political career==\nIn March 2017, Fransman threw his support behind chairperson of Nelson Mandela Bay African National Congress branch, Andile Lunigsa, as senior ANC party officials called for Lungisa's resignation.<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/marius-fransmans-ode-to-andile-lungisa-20170323 Marius Fransman's ode to Andile Lungisa]</ref>\n\nFransman, who is an avid supporter of Jacob Zuma, also announced in March 2017, that he is elated that Zuma reshuffled his cabinet and praised the appointments of the new ministers. He challenged the disgruntled ministers and MPs to resign their respective posts.<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/fransman-dares-unhappy-cabinet-ministers-to-resign-20170331 Fransman dares unhappy Cabinet ministers to resign]</ref>\n\nIn September 2018, the South African Jewish Board of Deputies made public statements, in which they stated that Fransman had not yet apologised for the defamatory comments he made in 2013.<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/marius-fransman-has-not-yet-apologised-for-2013-remarks-sa-jewish-board-20180928 Marius Fransman has not yet apologised for 2013 remarks - SA Jewish Board]</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, the National Prosecuting Authority announced that sexual assault claims made by Fransman's accuser, Louisa Wynand, would be investigated.<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/npa-to-prosecute-marius-fransman-20181208 NPA to prosecute Marius Fransman]</ref>\n\nThe sexual assault charges against Fransman were officially dropped in September 2019, after the two parties came to an agreement to settle out of court.<ref>[https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/npa-withdraws-sexual-assault-charges-against-marius-fransman-20190918 NPA withdraws sexual assault charges against Marius Fransman]. Retrieved on 19 September 2019.</ref> The ANC responded with the lifting of Fransman's suspension as a party member. Interim ANC Western Cape Chair, Lerumo Kalako, has said that Fransman is welcome to become a member of the party again.<ref>[https://ewn.co.za/2019/09/19/anc-says-fransman-can-return-to-party-after-sex-harassment-charges-withdrawn ANC says Fransman can return to party after sex harassment charges withdrawn]. Retrieved on 19 September 2019.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFransman is married to Philida Fransman. They have two children together. Fransman is a Christian and regularly attends church. He is a fluent speaker of Afrikaans and English.\n\nOn 31 March 2020, Fransman announced that he had tested positive for [[COVID-19]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Clothia |first1=Andrea |title=COVID-19: Former ANC chairperson Marius Fransman tests positive |url=https://www.thesouthafrican.com/news/covid-19-marius-fransman-tests-positive-for-coronavirus/ |accessdate=1 April 2020 |date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Pijoos |first1=Iavan |title=Former ANC Western Cape chair Marius Fransman tests positive for Covid-19 |url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2020-04-01-former-anc-western-cape-chair-marius-fransman-tests-positive-for-covid-19/ |accessdate=1 April 2020 |newspaper=TimesLIVE |date=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==External links==\n*[http://www.dirco.gov.za/department/profile_fransman.html Profile: Mr Marius Llewellyn Fransman \u2013 DIRCO]\n*[https://www.pa.org.za/person/marius-llewellyn-fransman/ Mr Marius Llewellyn Fransman \u2013 People's Assembly]\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box\n | title = [[Western Cape Provincial Parliament|Leader of the Opposition in the Western Cape Provincial Parliament]]\n | years = 2014\u20132016\n | before = [[Lynne Brown]]\n | after = Khaya Magaxa\n}}\n{{succession box\n | title = [[Department of International Relations and Cooperation|Deputy Minister of International Relations and Cooperation]]\n | years = 2010\u20132014\n | before = Sue van der Merwe\n | after 